Q: How to capture client request?
$ nc -l 80                          <-- start netcat on local machine @ port 80 (http)
$ nc -l 443                         <-- start netcat on local machine @ port 443 (https)

Q: How to capture server response?
curl -I www.google.com              <-- only headers
curl www.google.com                 <-- everything!

Q: How to do both?
GET /  www.google.com
in
Chromium developer tool
Button network
Tab cookie or headers
Name http:www.google.com


Q: Sample HTTP request?
telnet intranet 80
Trying 10.0.1.14...
Connected to intranet
Escape character is '^]'.
GET / HTTP/1.0
                                    <-- empty line is required !

Q: Sample HTTP response?
HTTP/1.1 200 OK
Date: Fri, 19 Oct 2012 22:53:13 GMT
Server: Apache/2.2.15 (Fedora)
Last-Modified: Thu, 29 Sep 2011 19:27:14 GMT
ETag: "1914007-b5d-4ae197ef14880"
Accept-Ranges: bytes
Content-Length: 2909
Connection: close
Content-Type: text/html; charset=UTF-8

Q: More advanced request?
GET / HTTP/1.1
Host: localhost:8080
Connection: keep-alive
User-Agent: Mozilla/5.0 (X11; Linux x86_64) AppleWebKit/536.11 (KHTML, like Gecko) Chrome/20.0.1132.47 Safari/536.11
Accept: text/html,application/xhtml+xml,application/xml;q=0.9,*/*;q=0.8
Accept-Encoding: gzip,deflate,sdch
Accept-Language: en-US,en;q=0.8
Accept-Charset: ISO-8859-1,utf-8;q=0.7,*;q=0.3

Q: HTTP is stateless. What does that mean?
HTTP is a 'stateless' protocol.   
This means that a server using basic authentication won't 'remember' you are logged in 
and will need to be sent the right header for every protected page you attempt to access.



